    <!-- Cancer Types -->
    <section class="cancer-types">
        <h2>Main Cancer Types in Sri Lanka</h2>
        <!-- Added image -->
        <img src="cancer.jpeg" alt="Cancer Awareness Image" class="section-img">

        <div class="cancer-card">
            <h3>Breast Cancer</h3>
            <p>Breast cancer originates in the ducts or lobules of the breast. Symptoms include painless lumps, changes in breast shape, nipple retraction, or discharge. Risk factors: age, family history, BRCA mutations, hormone exposure, lifestyle. Diagnostics: mammography, ultrasound, biopsy.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="cancer-card">
            <h3>Oral/Lip Cancer</h3>
            <p>Squamous cell carcinoma affecting mouth, tongue, gums, or lips. Symptoms: non-healing ulcers, red/white patches, persistent sores. Risk factors: tobacco, alcohol, HPV infection, sun exposure.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="cancer-card">
            <h3>Cervical Cancer</h3>
            <p>Arises from cervix lining, linked to persistent HPV infection. Early stages are asymptomatic; later signs include abnormal bleeding, pelvic pain, and discharge.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="cancer-card">
            <h3>Thyroid Cancer</h3>
            <p>Develops in thyroid gland, often as slow-growing nodules. Types: papillary, follicular, medullary, anaplastic. Symptoms: neck mass, hoarseness, difficulty swallowing, swollen lymph nodes. Diagnosis: ultrasound, fine-needle biopsy.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="cancer-card">
            <h3>Colorectal Cancer</h3>
            <p>Originates in colon/rectum, often from polyps. Symptoms: bowel habit changes, rectal bleeding, abdominal discomfort, weight loss, fatigue. Risk factors: age, family history, IBD, diet, smoking, sedentary lifestyle.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="cancer-card">
            <h3>Lung Cancer</h3>
            <p>Leading cause of cancer deaths. Strongly linked to tobacco smoking. Types: non-small cell (common), small cell (aggressive). Symptoms: persistent cough, chest pain, hemoptysis, shortness of breath.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Lifestyle Guidance -->
    <section class="lifestyle">
        <h2>Health Tips</h2>
        <!-- Added image -->
        <img src="awareness.jpg" alt="Health Awareness Tips Image" class="section-img">

        <h3>What To Do</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Eat 5+ servings of fruits/vegetables daily</li>
            <li>Exercise 150+ minutes weekly</li>
            <li>Maintain healthy weight (BMI 18.5-24.9)</li>
            <li>Use sunscreen daily (SPF 30+)</li>
            <li>Get recommended vaccinations (HPV, Hepatitis B)</li>
            <li>Limit alcohol consumption</li>
            <li>Get 7-9 hours of sleep nightly</li>
            <li>Drink plenty of water</li>
            <li>Practice stress management (meditation, yoga)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>What NOT To Do</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Avoid all tobacco products (smoking, vaping, chewing)</li>
            <li>Limit processed and red meats</li>
            <li>Reduce sugar and refined carbohydrates</li>
            <li>Avoid charred or overcooked foods</li>
            <li>Minimize sedentary behavior</li>
            <li>Don't ignore chronic stress</li>
            <li>Avoid unnecessary radiation exposure</li>
            <li>Don't skip regular check-ups</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- Screening Guidelines -->
    <section class="screening">
        <h2>Screening & Healthcare Routines</h2>

        <h3>For Women</h3>
        <p>Pap test every 3 years (21-65), HPV test every 5 years (30-65), mammogram yearly (40+), colonoscopy every 10 years (45+), skin cancer screening yearly, bone density test (65+).</p>

        <h3>For Men</h3>
        <p>PSA test discussion (50+, earlier if high risk), colonoscopy every 10 years (45+), lung CT scan for smokers (55-80), testicular self-exams monthly, skin cancer screening yearly.</p>

        <h3>For Everyone</h3>
        <p>Annual physical exam, dental check-ups every 6 months, eye exams regularly, vaccination updates, know family medical history.</p>
    </section>

    <!-- Nutrition -->
    <section class="nutrition">
        <h2>Healthy Diet & Nutrition Plans</h2>
        <p>Anti-Cancer Foods List:</p>
        <p>Cruciferous vegetables (broccoli, cauliflower, kale), berries (blueberries, strawberries, raspberries), tomatoes (lycopene-rich), garlic & onions (sulfur compounds), green tea (antioxidants), turmeric (curcumin), fatty fish (omega-3), whole grains (fiber-rich), legumes (beans, lentils), nuts & seeds (walnuts, flaxseeds).</p>
    </section>
